WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:20.000
I would like to welcome Alicia Schep.

00:00:20.000 --> 00:00:25.240
Hi my name is Alicia Schep and I'll be talking to you today about auto-magic package development

00:00:25.240 --> 00:00:32.279
or an effort to build a VegaLite interface in R that I call VLBuilder and if you're interested

00:00:32.279 --> 00:00:39.320
in the package at the end, the GitHub page is under the VegaWidget organization and in

00:00:39.320 --> 00:00:45.520
the readme to the package there is a link to the slides for this presentation.

00:00:45.520 --> 00:00:50.599
An alternate title I could have come up with here if I had a more literary bent would be

00:00:50.599 --> 00:00:55.880
a tale of two PRs because a lot of this work was motivated by a PR several years ago and

00:00:55.880 --> 00:01:01.639
recently vindicated by another one and so I'll be sharing about both of those in this

00:01:01.639 --> 00:01:02.639
talk.

00:01:02.639 --> 00:01:08.480
I want to start off first though talking about a little off topic about ggplot2 because ggplot2

00:01:08.480 --> 00:01:13.599
is what originally sold me on R. I did programming in Python before I learned R and I thought

00:01:13.599 --> 00:01:17.320
it was kind of awkward, kind of weird, but ggplot2 was amazing.

00:01:17.320 --> 00:01:20.800
I could do all of these things once I learned those basic building blocks, learned that

00:01:20.800 --> 00:01:24.360
underlying grammar, I could all of a sudden make all of these different kinds of plots

00:01:24.360 --> 00:01:29.320
and it felt really powerful and really special and so over the years even as I oscillated

00:01:29.320 --> 00:01:33.959
between using Python and R, I would always come back to R for the visualization part

00:01:33.959 --> 00:01:39.080
because ggplot2 was just so good and in my opinion nothing in Python really quite measured

00:01:39.080 --> 00:01:45.120
up, but that recently has changed and Python I feel like can now compete in the visualization

00:01:45.120 --> 00:01:48.239
domain and that's because of a package called Altair.

00:01:48.239 --> 00:01:51.040
If you use Python at all, I highly recommend checking it out.

00:01:51.040 --> 00:01:53.839
It's really amazing.

00:01:53.839 --> 00:01:58.919
Developed by Jake VanderPloss and Brian Granger and a whole team of folks and is still under

00:01:58.919 --> 00:02:03.120
active development and really well maintained.

00:02:03.120 --> 00:02:07.080
And it is like ggplot2 in many ways.

00:02:07.080 --> 00:02:11.919
It's built on top of a grammar of graphics so it has some of those same properties that

00:02:11.919 --> 00:02:15.080
once you learn the basic patterns, you can all of a sudden make all sorts of different

00:02:15.080 --> 00:02:16.080
kinds of visualizations.

00:02:16.080 --> 00:02:21.679
But it has in some ways even more powers than ggplot2 because it enables you to make interactive

00:02:21.679 --> 00:02:22.679
graphs.

00:02:22.679 --> 00:02:27.199
This is an example of a graph made by Altair just taken literally from the Altair example

00:02:27.199 --> 00:02:33.479
gallery where you're plotting in one graph like temperature over the year in Seattle,

00:02:33.479 --> 00:02:39.119
but then when you pan and brush, you can see different types of precipitation status over

00:02:39.119 --> 00:02:40.960
those time ranges.

00:02:40.960 --> 00:02:45.320
And this all looks very complicated, but in Altair it actually makes this very easy because

00:02:45.320 --> 00:02:48.639
it has those basic building blocks which you can easily tie together to make something

00:02:48.639 --> 00:02:49.639
like that.

00:02:49.639 --> 00:02:52.759
So it's not, this isn't, you know, if you were trying to make this in like D3, it would

00:02:52.759 --> 00:02:56.639
probably like take, well, it would at least take me like a year and many thousands of

00:02:56.639 --> 00:02:58.860
lines of code in Altair.

00:02:58.860 --> 00:03:01.520
This is just a little bit of Python code.

00:03:01.520 --> 00:03:06.880
And the reason it's so powerful is that Altair is built on top of VegaLite, which implements

00:03:06.880 --> 00:03:09.320
this interactive grammar of graphics.

00:03:09.320 --> 00:03:14.240
VegaLite itself is a higher level abstraction built on top of something else, Vega.

00:03:14.240 --> 00:03:19.960
And all this was developed by the Interactive Data Lab at the University of Washington.

00:03:19.960 --> 00:03:24.800
And just as a quick, you know, I'll be using some terms in this talk, just as quick ggplot2

00:03:24.800 --> 00:03:28.360
VegaLite terminology translations.

00:03:28.360 --> 00:03:31.360
Much more of you are familiar with ggplot2 than VegaLite.

00:03:31.360 --> 00:03:36.039
In ggplot2 where you'd talk about a geom, that's a mark, an aesthetic is an encoding,

00:03:36.039 --> 00:03:37.679
and a stat is a transform.

00:03:37.679 --> 00:03:41.960
But it has a lot of the same underlying concepts.

00:03:41.960 --> 00:03:48.240
VegaLite is in JavaScript and it uses a JSON specification to tell the plot what to draw

00:03:48.240 --> 00:03:52.639
and how to, what should be the mark, what should be the encoding, and so on.

00:03:52.639 --> 00:03:56.440
So if you actually try to make a plot this way, it can get a little bit clunky.

00:03:56.440 --> 00:04:02.279
Like building sort of nested lists isn't like the most fun way to program.

00:04:02.279 --> 00:04:06.720
It can be a little, you know, where exactly do you have to put all your curly braces and

00:04:06.720 --> 00:04:07.720
all.

00:04:07.720 --> 00:04:11.919
And this is where a package like Altair is really powerful because it builds an API on

00:04:11.919 --> 00:04:16.720
top of that so you don't have to worry too much about that complicated nested list.

00:04:16.720 --> 00:04:21.839
You can just use some ordinary Python methods to build up that plot.

00:04:21.839 --> 00:04:28.320
There's also now in JavaScript a nice API to build up those plots called VegaLite API.

00:04:28.320 --> 00:04:33.399
And in a number of different languages there are really great packages.

00:04:33.399 --> 00:04:39.440
So what I want is an R API for making VegaLite charts that hopefully is of a similar caliber

00:04:39.440 --> 00:04:43.160
as to some of those other ones that I just mentioned.

00:04:43.160 --> 00:04:49.279
And now some of you might be thinking, well, hasn't there been an R package that's even

00:04:49.279 --> 00:04:50.679
called VegaLite for many years?

00:04:50.679 --> 00:04:51.799
And you're absolutely right.

00:04:51.799 --> 00:04:57.640
And it has, it was developed by Bob Brutus and it is in many ways a really great package.

00:04:57.959 --> 00:05:02.399
It provides a really nice API where, you know, it uses the pipe that people are so familiar

00:05:02.399 --> 00:05:07.959
with where you can, you know, iteratively build up components of this plot.

00:05:07.959 --> 00:05:12.079
The thing is it's not up to date with some of the latest and greatest VegaLite features

00:05:12.079 --> 00:05:16.519
including some of those really killer features like the interactivity and the view composition

00:05:16.519 --> 00:05:19.959
where you can put different subplots together.

00:05:19.959 --> 00:05:23.480
And the reason it's not necessarily up to date is because it's actually, you know, when

00:05:23.480 --> 00:05:28.760
you build this sort of interface to this other thing, it can be kind of hard to update

00:05:28.760 --> 00:05:32.920
over time because it's, VegaLite is pretty big at this point.

00:05:32.920 --> 00:05:37.119
And so trying to keep it up to date is a pretty big endeavor.

00:05:37.119 --> 00:05:41.480
And I know that because I actually tried to update this package so many years ago.

00:05:41.480 --> 00:05:45.040
So when I told you this would be a tale of two PRs, this is that first one I would talk

00:05:45.040 --> 00:05:47.239
about.

00:05:47.239 --> 00:05:51.600
And so I wanted to, you know, the package was at VegaLite 1.0, I want to update it to

00:05:51.600 --> 00:05:52.600
VegaLite 2.0.

00:05:53.160 --> 00:05:57.720
So I spent quite a lot of time like going through and this was a massive PR.

00:05:57.720 --> 00:06:02.119
So just pro tip, if you're a first time contributor to a package, this is not what you should

00:06:02.119 --> 00:06:03.119
do.

00:06:03.119 --> 00:06:06.399
This is like exactly like the opposite of what you should do.

00:06:06.399 --> 00:06:13.320
Like I changed 88 files and like 48,000 or something lines of code.

00:06:13.320 --> 00:06:15.760
You know, it took a while for it to actually get accepted.

00:06:15.760 --> 00:06:17.600
It did eventually make its way in.

00:06:17.600 --> 00:06:21.239
But, you know, one of the things I learned was like this took a lot of work.

00:06:21.359 --> 00:06:25.440
And like the thing is the VegaLite developers are really productive.

00:06:25.440 --> 00:06:26.959
They're continuing to make improvements.

00:06:26.959 --> 00:06:34.839
And so like this method of like trying to keep this RAPI in line with this changing

00:06:34.839 --> 00:06:40.600
VegaLite definitions was just going to be a Herculean task.

00:06:40.600 --> 00:06:41.600
So I stepped back.

00:06:41.600 --> 00:06:44.880
I was like, okay, maybe I'll focus on other things.

00:06:44.880 --> 00:06:48.760
But then out of the blue someday, I got an email from Ian Little.

00:06:48.760 --> 00:06:55.839
And he was embarking on a new effort, which was to actually make a port to VegaLite through

00:06:55.839 --> 00:06:59.000
Altair using the reticulate package.

00:06:59.000 --> 00:07:03.559
So in some ways it's a little funny using Python to get to JavaScript, but it actually

00:07:03.559 --> 00:07:04.559
works really well.

00:07:04.559 --> 00:07:09.600
And he was working with Haley Jepsen and Heikki Hoffman from Iowa.

00:07:09.600 --> 00:07:12.160
And this package is now on CRAN.

00:07:12.160 --> 00:07:16.359
It's also available here at VegaWidget Altair.

00:07:16.359 --> 00:07:20.040
And so I was really excited by this effort, and I got involved, and I started to chip

00:07:20.040 --> 00:07:23.200
into that package.

00:07:23.200 --> 00:07:29.679
I think my biggest contribution was actually suggesting to Ian that maybe he could split

00:07:29.679 --> 00:07:36.200
off one part of the package into something else, which is that he was using Altair to

00:07:36.200 --> 00:07:39.440
use some code to make that specification for what the chart should be.

00:07:39.440 --> 00:07:43.279
But then another big part of the code was just taking that specification and rendering

00:07:43.279 --> 00:07:45.320
it in R so you could actually see the plot.

00:07:45.320 --> 00:07:50.079
And I said, well, maybe we should make that a separate package to just do the render.

00:07:50.079 --> 00:07:52.959
And so that became the VegaWidget package.

00:07:52.959 --> 00:07:58.720
So VegaWidget just takes a JSON spec and then uses the HTML widgets package in R to turn

00:07:58.720 --> 00:08:00.559
it into a plot.

00:08:00.559 --> 00:08:04.959
And this was primarily developed by Ian, who actually at this very minute is giving a talk

00:08:04.959 --> 00:08:09.200
in another room, which is kind of unfortunate timing.

00:08:09.200 --> 00:08:14.320
But he's a really smart, very nice guy.

00:08:14.320 --> 00:08:18.640
You should go find him and talk to him if you're interested in any of this stuff.

00:08:18.640 --> 00:08:25.799
And myself and Stuart Lee helped with some of the JavaScript functionality in this package.

00:08:25.799 --> 00:08:31.160
And so what this package also does is it provides interfaces from that HTML widget to other

00:08:31.160 --> 00:08:34.960
parts of the R ecosystem, in particular Shiny.

00:08:34.960 --> 00:08:40.159
So it has functions to help you listen to events, to connect to what in Vega world is

00:08:40.159 --> 00:08:45.119
called a signal, which is basically a dynamic data value, and also to let you update the

00:08:45.119 --> 00:08:50.039
data that's in the plot without completely re-rendering it.

00:08:50.039 --> 00:08:52.640
What VegaWidget doesn't do is it doesn't help you make the spec.

00:08:52.640 --> 00:08:59.039
So it basically expects some JSON to be given to it, which in R form is going to be basically

00:08:59.039 --> 00:09:01.559
a big, complicated, nested list.

00:09:01.559 --> 00:09:04.400
So this isn't a package that you're usually going to want to use directly.

00:09:04.400 --> 00:09:08.159
You're not going to want to go and make this kind of list because it's a little bit clunky

00:09:08.159 --> 00:09:13.520
and you'd have to store in your head exactly how to make this kind of thing.

00:09:13.520 --> 00:09:18.640
But this package is designed to be a helper to other packages, where those other packages

00:09:18.640 --> 00:09:19.960
would help you make the spec.

00:09:19.960 --> 00:09:24.119
And then they can rely on the shared interface to actually render it.

00:09:24.119 --> 00:09:30.880
So one of those packages is an R port to the Altair package, which uses Altair via reticulate

00:09:30.880 --> 00:09:33.840
to actually make that spec and then gets rendered.

00:09:34.799 --> 00:09:40.400
Ian and Haley and others are now working on ggvega, which is a package to take a ggplot

00:09:40.400 --> 00:09:45.440
object, turn it into one of those specs, and then have it render.

00:09:45.440 --> 00:09:50.080
And then I've been working on VLBuilder, which is basically, in some ways, like a spiritual

00:09:50.080 --> 00:09:55.880
successor to that VegaLite package, which tries to make a native R API to make these

00:09:55.880 --> 00:09:59.359
specs, which then can be rendered via VegaWidget.

00:09:59.359 --> 00:10:03.760
So the goals of VLBuilder were they wanted a pipe-friendly approach for building up VegaLite

00:10:03.760 --> 00:10:04.760
specs.

00:10:04.760 --> 00:10:07.960
They wanted something that felt sort of natural to an R user who might be familiar with the

00:10:07.960 --> 00:10:08.960
tidyverse.

00:10:08.960 --> 00:10:14.760
They wanted to stay pretty close to the VegaLite spec, so not inventing new abstractions, not

00:10:14.760 --> 00:10:21.239
inventing new terminology, but just kind of taking what is in VegaLite and making it accessible

00:10:21.239 --> 00:10:25.520
in R. But maybe a little syntactic sugar here and there for when you have common things

00:10:25.520 --> 00:10:29.440
to do that might be a little clunky and trying to make those a little easier.

00:10:29.440 --> 00:10:33.840
Another key thing I wanted was to have autocomplete and documentation help, so that, you know,

00:10:33.840 --> 00:10:37.520
if you're trying to add an encoding, you can see what are the different parameters I can

00:10:37.520 --> 00:10:38.520
give to that.

00:10:38.520 --> 00:10:42.359
And that's something that actually is a little bit missing from the Altair package, because

00:10:42.359 --> 00:10:44.119
it's going through Articulate.

00:10:44.119 --> 00:10:46.479
You kind of end up having to really use it effectively.

00:10:46.479 --> 00:10:48.760
You often have to end up going to the Python docs.

00:10:48.760 --> 00:10:56.080
They're not quite as easy to access for an R user in RStudio.

00:10:56.080 --> 00:11:00.080
And the most important thing, well, in my mind, developing this, was that it had to

00:11:00.080 --> 00:11:03.719
be fun to develop and easy to update as the VegaLite scheme evolved, because I learned

00:11:03.719 --> 00:11:07.440
from that other PR that, like, you know, if you just, you know, try to build something

00:11:07.440 --> 00:11:14.320
up manually that tries to match VegaLite, it's going to take a lot of work when VegaLite

00:11:14.320 --> 00:11:16.599
evolves.

00:11:16.599 --> 00:11:20.119
And I didn't want to get caught in that same bind again.

00:11:20.119 --> 00:11:27.039
So here I took inspiration from Altair and the VegaLite API packages, because both of

00:11:27.039 --> 00:11:33.559
those approaches in Python and JavaScript respectively actually auto-generate big parts

00:11:33.559 --> 00:11:36.359
of their API using VegaLite itself.

00:11:36.359 --> 00:11:42.719
So VegaLite has a schema which can derive what a VegaLite specification should look

00:11:42.719 --> 00:11:43.719
like.

00:11:43.719 --> 00:11:45.960
You can use that to build up an API.

00:11:45.960 --> 00:11:49.679
So I thought, why don't I try to do this in R too?

00:11:49.679 --> 00:11:54.599
So just to go a little bit more into, like, what a schema is and what I mean by that,

00:11:54.599 --> 00:11:58.760
the VegaLite schema is basically telling you in that, like, kind of JSON, that list object

00:11:58.760 --> 00:12:03.520
where you're specifying the different parts of the plot, what is an acceptable sort of

00:12:03.520 --> 00:12:05.320
format for each of those parts?

00:12:05.320 --> 00:12:09.679
So for example, you know, you might say here an aggregate can be one of these other three

00:12:09.679 --> 00:12:14.039
types and then this type can be one of these 12 different values.

00:12:14.039 --> 00:12:17.880
Hopefully, it also includes descriptions for what different fields mean.

00:12:17.880 --> 00:12:22.440
So in terms of trying to build up the documentation, a lot of what you'd want as documentation

00:12:22.440 --> 00:12:28.440
is actually embedded in this schema document.

00:12:28.440 --> 00:12:35.159
And so the approach I took for building an R API from a JSON schema was one of semi-automation.

00:12:35.159 --> 00:12:38.919
So early on, I was like, oh, maybe I'll try to automate it as much as possible.

00:12:38.919 --> 00:12:43.960
But at some point, like, making something very generalized and totally automated becomes

00:12:43.960 --> 00:12:45.280
a very hard problem.

00:12:45.280 --> 00:12:51.000
And so I try to strike the right balance between using some human curation and some automation.

00:12:51.000 --> 00:12:56.119
So the human curation part is sort of identifying what families of functions do I want.

00:12:56.119 --> 00:13:02.760
So I know that, you know, an encoding is going to be a very important part to make a VegaLite

00:13:02.760 --> 00:13:03.760
spec.

00:13:03.760 --> 00:13:08.960
I'm going to want a bunch of different functions that let you add different kinds of encoding.

00:13:08.960 --> 00:13:10.880
I'm also going to want that for a mark.

00:13:10.880 --> 00:13:12.640
So the mark is sort of like the geom and geom.

00:13:12.640 --> 00:13:18.599
So I want, like, a VL mark point, VL mark bar, VL mark line, et cetera.

00:13:18.599 --> 00:13:21.479
And so I'm going to want all these different kinds of families of functions, and they're

00:13:21.479 --> 00:13:23.580
going to have this kind of format.

00:13:23.580 --> 00:13:28.239
But in terms of figuring out exactly which ones I need and what's going to go inside

00:13:28.239 --> 00:13:32.559
them, what are the acceptable parameters, there I'm going to use automation.

00:13:32.559 --> 00:13:37.479
I'm going to pull those things out of the schema and plop them into my function rather

00:13:37.479 --> 00:13:40.479
than doing that manually by copying and pasting.

00:13:40.479 --> 00:13:43.640
I'm going to write functions to do that.

00:13:43.640 --> 00:13:48.159
And so all of this sort of functions to build these functions lives in a package within

00:13:48.159 --> 00:13:49.159
my package.

00:13:49.159 --> 00:13:53.840
So if you look in VL builder, there's a build directory, and inside of that, there's a package

00:13:53.840 --> 00:14:00.080
I call VL metabuilder, which is the package that builds VL builder, and the main function

00:14:00.080 --> 00:14:04.440
is one that's called just create API, and it takes as an argument the schema.

00:14:04.440 --> 00:14:09.080
So as the schema updates, as there's a new version of that schema, I can give it that

00:14:09.080 --> 00:14:16.599
new version, and I'll create a new API.

00:14:16.599 --> 00:14:22.700
And so as an example of how to make a family of functions, I have that create API function

00:14:22.700 --> 00:14:26.960
called something called create encoding functions, which will make all those encoding functions.

00:14:26.960 --> 00:14:31.719
It first will pull all the possible encoding, so it'll take a function that says, okay,

00:14:31.719 --> 00:14:35.239
this is where in the schema I'm going to look for them, and has a function to then pull

00:14:35.239 --> 00:14:38.440
out all the different options that would be available.

00:14:38.799 --> 00:14:43.799
It then iterates through all of them and makes the appropriate functions.

00:14:43.799 --> 00:14:47.200
So here, actually, I make sort of for each encoding, I want both a function that will

00:14:47.200 --> 00:14:51.640
sort of add one to spec or one that just makes that object on its own.

00:14:51.640 --> 00:14:56.520
You can see there's some deprecation, so I have even functions to generate my deprecated

00:14:56.520 --> 00:15:01.080
versions of my functions as well.

00:15:01.080 --> 00:15:07.440
And so here, in terms of what a function to make a function is, here I have my create

00:15:07.440 --> 00:15:11.440
encoder function that calls another function, because a lot of them actually share a lot

00:15:11.440 --> 00:15:12.440
of properties.

00:15:12.440 --> 00:15:18.679
So I have a generalized make function that takes in, most importantly, where to look

00:15:18.679 --> 00:15:19.679
in the schema.

00:15:19.679 --> 00:15:25.400
So this is a path to a particular place in that specification for what can go in a particular

00:15:25.400 --> 00:15:30.440
part of a Vega-Lite spec, and it looks like what are all the available options.

00:15:30.440 --> 00:15:34.640
And then there's a couple extra things where I specify, as you can tell, like one thing

00:15:34.679 --> 00:15:37.440
that gets used a lot in this effort is glue.

00:15:37.440 --> 00:15:41.719
The glue package is really handy for this kind of effort, because you're basically trying

00:15:41.719 --> 00:15:45.520
to make a bunch of strings where you're putting different pieces together.

00:15:45.520 --> 00:15:49.000
So that has come in really handy in this effort.

00:15:49.000 --> 00:15:53.320
And so then it ends up making a function that also has documentation, because it actually

00:15:53.320 --> 00:15:56.760
pulls all those little pieces of documentation out of that schema object.

00:15:56.760 --> 00:15:58.559
And so I don't have to write any of it.

00:15:58.559 --> 00:16:03.960
I can just use what's already been created, but make it accessible in R in a way that

00:16:04.280 --> 00:16:05.919
the R user doesn't have to go to some website.

00:16:05.919 --> 00:16:12.719
They can just type in help and get it right there in their RStudio pane.

00:16:12.719 --> 00:16:16.799
This is just one of hundreds of functions generated by VL MetaBuilder.

00:16:16.799 --> 00:16:21.280
Now this was recently, this package and the approach I took was recently put to the test,

00:16:21.280 --> 00:16:29.239
because in December Vega-Lite 4 came out, which added new features, new transforms.

00:16:29.239 --> 00:16:34.239
And so it was like, okay, well, now previously I've been using Vega-Lite 3 to generate my

00:16:34.239 --> 00:16:35.239
API.

00:16:35.239 --> 00:16:38.440
I want to make it compatible with version 4.

00:16:38.440 --> 00:16:43.559
Hopefully my automation will just take care of it, and I can just sit back and relax.

00:16:43.559 --> 00:16:46.520
And that actually did come to bear.

00:16:46.520 --> 00:16:55.239
So it was another large PR, this time to my own repository, which helps a little bit.

00:16:55.239 --> 00:17:00.840
But behind the sort of numbers that, you know, 190 files changed and tens of thousands

00:17:00.840 --> 00:17:03.960
of lines of code, there was actually very little work on my part.

00:17:03.960 --> 00:17:08.760
This took just literally like an hour or two, one day.

00:17:08.760 --> 00:17:13.000
When I first put in the new schema, one thing broke, I fixed that, and then all of a sudden

00:17:13.000 --> 00:17:14.680
it kind of just worked.

00:17:14.680 --> 00:17:20.040
And that felt really, having gone through that earlier, experience really great.

00:17:20.040 --> 00:17:25.400
And you can kind of see that in some of the more detailed descriptions that GitHub will

00:17:25.400 --> 00:17:26.400
give you.

00:17:26.400 --> 00:17:30.719
So, like, in terms of all those lines of code changing, a lot of them were actually just

00:17:30.719 --> 00:17:35.000
in the schema file that gets included in the repository itself.

00:17:35.000 --> 00:17:39.400
But then the other thing is I had this file called autogen API, which is all what gets

00:17:39.400 --> 00:17:43.880
auto-generated by VL MetaBuilder, and lots of stuff changed there, but in most of my

00:17:43.880 --> 00:17:47.640
other files, very little changed.

00:17:47.640 --> 00:17:50.839
And then in terms of which files were changing, actually a lot of the files changing were

00:17:50.839 --> 00:17:55.079
the documentation files, which all, pretty much all, are being, like, sort of auto-generated

00:17:55.079 --> 00:18:00.400
through auto-generated Roxygen documentation.

00:18:00.400 --> 00:18:04.160
So, you know, if you're ever finding yourself writing a bunch of repetitive functions and

00:18:04.160 --> 00:18:10.359
documentations, which can often happen when you're writing a wrapper package, I'd recommend

00:18:10.359 --> 00:18:12.560
writing another package to write your package.

00:18:12.560 --> 00:18:17.560
It can actually end up being less work for you down the road.

00:18:18.479 --> 00:18:20.239
And, of course, I'm not the only one that's had this idea.

00:18:20.239 --> 00:18:26.680
Other folks have, you know, put in place efforts to auto-generate code in R. So, Miles just

00:18:26.680 --> 00:18:30.319
recently asked a question about whether people were doing this, and there was a great thread

00:18:30.319 --> 00:18:35.400
of different people who were doing this, and he put some of those suggestions into place

00:18:35.400 --> 00:18:37.920
and into a package he's developing.

00:18:37.920 --> 00:18:41.760
There's also a scaffolder package that's being developed that I think is actually trying

00:18:41.760 --> 00:18:46.800
to be a much more general solution to this, which I'm really excited about that package

00:18:47.040 --> 00:18:50.640
and other efforts in this vein.

00:18:50.640 --> 00:18:55.280
And so, finally, I just want to leave you with a little bit of a reminder that this

00:18:55.280 --> 00:19:00.800
whole Vega widget ecosystem exists in R. If you're interested in making interactive graphics

00:19:00.800 --> 00:19:04.040
using VegaLite in R, I'd recommend checking it out.

00:19:04.040 --> 00:19:07.439
At this point, the Altair and Vega widget packages are fairly mature.

00:19:07.439 --> 00:19:08.839
They're both on CRAN.

00:19:08.839 --> 00:19:13.280
The other packages are a little bit still more experimental, and there's a great community

00:19:13.280 --> 00:19:16.760
of people involved in these efforts.

00:19:16.760 --> 00:19:19.239
There's also, I think, opportunity for new APIs.

00:19:19.239 --> 00:19:24.119
If you're itching to make a higher-level API for interactive graphics, I think the Vega

00:19:24.119 --> 00:19:30.319
widget package makes that effort easier, because if you can just make that VegaLite spec, it

00:19:30.319 --> 00:19:32.880
can then do the whole rendering part.

00:19:32.880 --> 00:19:38.359
And so I'm really excited to potentially see more experimentation in this space, because

00:19:38.359 --> 00:19:44.479
I think that, yeah, the Vega widget package makes that kind of experimentation possible.

00:19:44.479 --> 00:19:46.560
And so, yeah, that is my talk.

00:19:47.359 --> 00:19:51.400
And if you're interested, again, I'll point you to GitHub, where the package lives, as

00:19:51.400 --> 00:19:56.959
well as all those packages live in that Vega widget organization on GitHub.

00:19:56.959 --> 00:19:59.680
And the link to those slides is in the readme for VLBuilder.

00:19:59.680 --> 00:20:00.680
Thank you.

00:20:00.680 --> 00:20:00.680


